06632nam a22009495i 9780231527699DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011021226  a(OCoLC)979969533  a97802315276997 a10.7312/krim156962doi  a(DE-B1597)459025  a(OCoLC)758823272  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aGN289b.R33 2011 4aQH430 7aSCI0290002bisacsh04a576.522300aRace and the Genetic Revolution :bScience, Myth, and Culture /ced. by Kathleen Sloan, Sheldon Krimsky. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b1 illus; 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: How Science Embraced the Racialization of Human Populations -- tPart I: Science and Race -- t1. A Short History of the Race Concept -- t2. Natural Selection, the Human Genome, and the Idea of Race -- tPart II: Forensic DNA Databases, Race, and the Criminal Justice System -- t3. Racial Disparities in Databanking of DNA Profiles -- t4. Prejudice, Stigma, and DNA Databases -- tPart III: Ancestry Testing -- t5. Ancestry Testing and DNA -- t6. Can DNA “Witness” Race? -- tPart IV: Racialized Medicine -- t7. Bidil and Racialized Medicine -- t8. Evolutionary Versus Racial Medicine -- tPart V: Intelligence and Race -- t9. Myth and Mystification -- t10. Intelligence, Race, and Genetics -- tPart VI: Contemporary Culture, Race, and Genetics -- t11. The Elusive Variability of Race -- t12. Race, Genetics, and the Regulatory Need for Race Impact Assessments -- tConclusion -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDo advances in genomic biology create a scientific rationale for long-discredited racial categories? Leading scholars in law, medicine, biology, sociology, history, anthropology, and psychology examine the impact of modern genetics on the concept of race. Contributors trace the interplay between genetics and race in forensic DNA databanks, the biology of intelligence, DNA ancestry markers, and racialized medicine. Each essay explores commonly held and unexamined assumptions and misperceptions about race in science and popular culture.This collection begins with the historical origins and current uses of the concept of "race" in science. It follows with an analysis of the role of race in DNA databanks and racial disparities in the criminal justice system. Essays then consider the rise of recreational genetics in the form of for-profit testing of genetic ancestry and the introduction of racialized medicine, specifically through an FDA-approved heart drug called BiDil, marketed to African American men. Concluding sections discuss the contradictions between our scientific and cultural understandings of race and the continuing significance of race in educational and criminal justice policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAufsatzsammlung. 0aGenetics. 0aHuman geneticsxVariation. 0aHuman population genetics. 0aMolecular evolution. 0aRace. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Genetics & Genomics.2bisacsh1 aDuster, Troy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFullwiley, Duana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraves, Joseph L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrigorenko, Elena L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammonds, Evelynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahn, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKidd, Kenneth K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela